                                        </mml:msubsup>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                </mml:math>
                            </inline-formula> is the Standard deviation;</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <p>w
                            <sub>ij</sub> is the weight matrix.</p>
                    </list-item>
                </list>
                <p>The area units considered need to be weighted by means of a contiguity matrix, reproducing the spatial relationship among the regions considered, using a binary set of existing / non existing contiguity among the different areas, following a &#x2018;Queen rule&#x2019; of connection (
                    <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-1">Anselin, 1995</xref>).</p>
                <p>From the application of the above mentioned method it is possible to obtain five combinations:</p>
                <list list-type="bullet">
                    <list-item>
                        <label>(1)</label>
                        <p>high values of the phenomenon and high levels of similarity with the nearby areas, known hot spots (High-High), observable on the upper right quadrant of the global Moran&#x2019;s I graph;</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <label>(2)</label>
                        <p>low values of the phenomenon and low levels of similarity with the nearby areas, called cold spots (Low-Low); observable on the lower left quadrant of the global Moran&#x2019;s I graph</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <label>(3)</label>
                        <p>high values of the phenomenon and low levels of similarity with the nearby areas are detected, referred to as potential outliers (High-Low);</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <label>(4)</label>
                        <p>low values of the phenomenon and high levels of similarity with nearby areas are highlighted, referred to as potential outliers (Low-High);</p>
                    </list-item>
                    <list-item>
                        <label>(5)</label>
                        <p>no significant autocorrelation values are detected (Not Significant).</p>
                    </list-item>
                </list>
                <p>Spatial autocorrelation can be also considered as a bivariate one, typically as the correlation between one variable and the spatial lag of another variable. In the case considered, the implemented indicator, IRE, was related to measures of local GDP in order to understand the existence of a possible relationship among the different variable and their spatial extent. Recently LISA&#x2019;s local Moran&#x2019;s I was used to analyse, among others, socio economic phenomena on area unit data on various applications, from migration movements (
                    <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-10">Borruso, 2009</xref>; 
                    <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-41">Murgante &amp; Borruso, 2012</xref>) to the efficacy of cohesion policies (
                    <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-5">Balletto 
                        <italic toggle="yes">et al.,</italic> 2020</xref>). The analysis was performed using GeoDA as Free and Open Source Software, as developed by 
                    <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-1">Anselin (1995)</xref>.</p>
            </sec>
        </sec>
        <sec sec-type="results">
            <title>4. Results</title>
            <p>IRE applied to the 245 European NUTS 1 and NUTS 2 units considered was related to per capita GDP values in &#x20ac; at 2021 and a set of analyses were performed, as anticipated in the methods above. Namely, the regression analysis and the Local Moran over the IRE index. As an early, visual observation of the IRE maps realized portrayed a certain level of similarity of most innovative regions with the highest GDP&#x2019;s ones, as those of the European core or the heart of the so-called &#x2018;Blue Banana&#x2019; (
                <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="ref-13">Brunet, 1989</xref>), a regression analysis was initially carried out to observe if a certain relationship among the variables could be considered. IRE and GDP values were plotted, and a linear regression performed, providing interesting results given the high level of relation that can be observed among the different variables (R
                <sup>2</sup> of 0.525; 
                <xref ref-type="fig" rid="f8">Figure 8 a</xref>) in the direct relationship, and better fitting values considering Ln GDP (R
                <sup>2</sup> of 0.6256; 
                <xref ref-type="fig" rid="f8">Figure 8 b</xref>).</p>
            <fig fig-type="figure" id="f8" orientation="portrait" position="float">
                <label>Figure 8. </label>
                <caption>
                    <p>Regression Analysis 
                        <bold>a</bold>) IRE and GDP; 
                        <bold>b</bold>) IRE &#x2013; Ln GDP. Source: elaboration from GISCO &#x2013; Eurostat data; Data as in 
                        <xref ref-type="table" rid="T1">Table 1</xref>. Graph by Giuseppe Borruso.</p>
                </caption>
                <graphic orientation="portrait" position="float"
                     xlink:href="https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/openreseurope/manuscripts/18166/aceb7940-60e9-4b52-9899-e19f507ddaf4_figure8.gif"/>
            </fig>
            <p>Such initial results induced us to consider the spatial component and behaviour of both IRE and of its relationship with European GDP. As in previous paragraph, Global and Local Moran&#x2019;s I were performed on IRE (
                <xref ref-type="fig" rid="f9">Figure 9</xref> and 
                <xref ref-type="fig" rid="f10">Figure 10</xref>), Ln GDP (
                <xref ref-type="fig" rid="f11">Figure 11</xref> and 
                <xref ref-type="fig" rid="f12">Figure 12</xref>) and as a crossed, bivariate Moran&#x2019;s I on IRE and Ln GDP (
                <xref ref-type="fig" rid="f13">Figure 13</xref> and 
                <xref ref-type="fig" rid="f14">Figure 14</xref>).</p>
            <p>Local Moran&#x2019;s application present spatial clusters of high-high autocorrelation of the IRE in the NUTS areas in proximity of the European core, covering from Eastern France, Southern Germany, part of Austria and Belgium, as well as most of England units. Scandinavian peninsula&#x2019;s units represent a relevant cluster as well. Negative autocorrelation can be observed on a wide cluster of units belonging to Eastern European countries, as well as on one in Southern Spain (
                <xref ref-type="fig" rid="f9">Figure 9</xref>).</p>
            <fig fig-type="figure" id="f9" orientation="portrait" position="float">
                <label>Figure 9. </label>
                <caption>
                    <title>Local Moran&#x2019;s I Cluster Map on IRE.</title>
                    <p>Source: elaboration from GISCO &#x2013; Eurostat data; Data as in 
                        <xref ref-type="table" rid="T1">Table 1</xref>. Map by Giuseppe Borruso.</p>
                </caption>
                <graphic orientation="portrait" position="float"
                     xlink:href="https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/openreseurope/manuscripts/18166/aceb7940-60e9-4b52-9899-e19f507ddaf4_figure9.gif"/>
            </fig>
            <p>Cluster map appears significant, with a relevant value of Moran&#x2019;s I (0,708; 
                <xref ref-type="fig" rid="f10">Figure 10 a and b</xref>).</p>
            <fig fig-type="figure" id="f10" orientation="portrait" position="float">
                <label>Figure 10. </label>
                <caption>
                    <p>
                        <bold>
                            <italic toggle="yes">a</italic>
                        </bold>) Local Moran&#x2019;s I Significance map on IRE and 
                        <bold>
                            <italic toggle="yes">b</italic>
                        </bold>) Moran&#x2019;s I. Source: elaboration from GISCO &#x2013; Eurostat data; Data as in 
                        <xref ref-type="table" rid="T1">Table 1</xref>. Map and graph by Giuseppe Borruso.</p>
                </caption>
                <graphic orientation="portrait" position="float"
                     xlink:href="https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/openreseurope/manuscripts/18166/aceb7940-60e9-4b52-9899-e19f507ddaf4_figure10.gif"/>
            </fig>
            <p>Cluster map appears significant, with a relevant value of Moran&#x2019;s I (0,708; 
                <xref ref-type="fig" rid="f10">Figure 10 a and b</xref>).</p>
            <p>Univariate local Moran&#x2019;s I was performed also on Ln GDP, reporting a &#x2013; quite expectable &#x2013; autocorrelation and spatial clustering of areas in the European economic core, rooted into Northern Italian Regions and extended northwards through Southern and Western Germany, Eastern France, BeNeLux and Ireland. Scandinavian regions represent another clusters. A East-West division appears with the wide cluster of negative autocorrelation regarding the regions belonging to Eastern European countries (
                <xref ref-type="fig" rid="f11">Figure 11</xref>).</p>
            <fig fig-type="figure" id="f11" orientation="portrait" position="float">
                <label>Figure 11. </label>
                <caption>
                    <title>Local Moran&#x2019;s I Cluster Map on Ln GDP.</title>
                    <p>Source: elaboration from GISCO &#x2013; Eurostat data; Data as in 
                        <xref ref-type="table" rid="T1">Table 1</xref>. Map by Giuseppe Borruso.</p>
                </caption>
                <graphic orientation="portrait" position="float"
                     xlink:href="https://s3-eu-west-1.amazonaws.com/openreseurope/manuscripts/18166/aceb7940-60e9-4b52-9899-e19f507ddaf4_figure11.gif"/>
            </fig>
            <p>Also in this case cluster map appears significant, with a relevant value of Moran&#x2019;s I (0,788; 
                <xref ref-type="fig" rid="f12">Figure 12 a and b</xref>).</p>
